<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate rafter length?", answer: "Use the Pythagorean theorem. Rafter length = √(run² + rise²), where run is half the building width and rise = run × (pitch ÷ 12). For a 24 ft wide building with a 6/12 pitch: run = 12, rise = 6, rafter = √(144 + 36) = √180 ≈ 13.42 ft. Add overhang separately if you want the total length of stock to order." },
  { question: "What is roof pitch?", answer: "Roof pitch is the number of inches of vertical rise for every 12 inches of horizontal run. A 4/12 pitch rises 4 inches over 12 inches of run — a gentle, common residential slope. 6/12 is steeper, 12/12 equals 45 degrees, and 3/12 or lower is considered a low-slope roof and uses different roofing materials (membrane rather than shingles)." },
  { question: "What is the difference between run and span?", answer: "Span is the total width of the building from outside wall to outside wall. Run is half the span, or half the distance between the two supporting walls. Rafters are laid out from the run (from the wall plate to the ridge), so always use the run — not the span — in the calculator." },
  { question: "How much overhang should a rafter have?", answer: "Standard eave overhangs are 12 to 24 inches. Shorter overhangs look modern but expose siding to rain, while longer overhangs (up to 36 inches) provide better shade and siding protection in hot or wet climates. Overhang is measured horizontally from the wall to the tip of the rafter tail — the calculator converts this to additional rafter length." },
  { question: "How do I convert roof pitch to degrees?", answer: "Take the pitch as a fraction (rise ÷ 12) and use arctangent: angle = atan(rise/12). Common conversions: 4/12 = 18.4°, 6/12 = 26.6°, 8/12 = 33.7°, 12/12 = 45°. The calculator shows degrees and percent grade automatically." }
]) %>

